elements.author: vritikas
elements.name: How Do I Test OCL Queries (OCL Query Tool)?
elements.qualifiedName: /////Architectural Patterns & Examples/////How Do I Test OCL Queries (OCL Query Tool)?
elements.documentation:
Test out your OCL expressions in MagicDraw by

  1. selecting some model elements in a diagram or the containment tree,
  2. finding the MDK menu, and
  3. selecting "Run OCL Query." 
  4. You may need to resize the popup window to see the entry fields. 
  5. Enter an expression in OCL, hit OK, and see the result (or error).

There are four parts to the OCL Evaluator:

1. Expression entry

In this area you can enter an OCL query and recall previously evaluated queries by clicking on the arrow on the right hand side of the field.

2. Results

This is where the results of the query are displayed.

3. Query completion suggestions

This field suggests potential options for the current result of your query.

4. Selection location

This allows you to select from which location "Self" or the target of the query should be taken from.

elements.name: How Do I Install Magic Draw with MDK?
elements.qualifiedName: /////Architectural Patterns & Examples////How Do I Install Magic Draw with MDK?
elements.documentation:
Mac Users -

Optional: This set of instructions is a recommended best practice only, location of MD install does not impact custom icon for Mac Users

  1. Open the Finder and Click on Applications in the left hand side                          
  2. Click on the new folder icon in the upper left corner of the window and name the new folder "MagicDraw". If you already have a Magic Draw installation in a "MagicDraw" folder, create a NEW folder in the Applications folder. Either rename your old MagicDraw folder or name this new folder something else (i.e. "Bender_1.1"). Do NOT install multiple Magic Draw installations in the same folder                                                                                                                                                                                    
  3. Download Latest MD Release from the EMS Support site on "ems.jpl.nasa.gov"
  4. Copy the downloaded .zip to \Applications\MagicDraw\ (or corresponding folder) and double click to extract it
  5. Open the newly extracted Folder and locate "MagicDraw UML". Clicking this starts MagicDraw.
  6. It is recommended to create a shortcut in your OSX Dock. To do so, select "MagicDraw UML" and drag it down to your Dock.          

Windows Users -

  1. Download Latest MD Release from the EMS Support site on "ems.jpl.nasa.gov"
  2. Extract MagicDraw to the location of your choice (Recommended C:\MagicDraw\). Do NOT install multiple Magic Draw installations in the same folder. If you already have a Magic Draw installation in a "MagicDraw" folder, create a NEW folder in the Applications folder. Either rename your old MagicDraw folder or name this new folder something else (i.e. "Bender_1.1").
  3. Open the bin folder in the extracted Magic Draw installation folder.
  4. Click on mduml.exe to open Magic Draw.
  5. It is recommended to create a shortcut (either on your Desktop or your task bar). To do this, right click on mduml.exe and select Send To...->Desktop (create shortcut).
  6. Navigate to your desktop and right click on on the Shortcut and click Rename. Enter "MagicDraw UML" and then click enter.
  7. Now right click on "MagicDraw UML" and select Properties             
  8. In the Properties window click "Change Icon..."                                              
  9. The Change Icon dialog will open, select Browse... and Navigate to the installation's bin folder. Select the \Europa_%ReleaseName%_Logo_256.ico and click Open.                                                         
  10. Hit Apply and OK
  11. Now either leave the shortcut on your Desktop or drag it to your taskbar.
  12. Double-click on the shortcut to open MagicDraw!

elements.name: How Do I Edit a Bulleted List or Table?
elements.qualifiedName: /////Architectural Patterns & Examples/////How Do I Edit a Bulleted List or Table?
elements.documentation:
Bulleted lists and tables generated by a viewpoint from the model can be edited the same way as any text field. However these elements have been "Cross-Referenced" meaning that each field shown is actually a model element that is related in some way. This is a powerful feature that allows users to update important information between the model and View Editor. Below are two examples of editable tables and a bulleted list. Feel free to experiment with these elements, they are non mission critical and are examples of some of the powerful capabilities available to View Editor users.

1. Select Show Elements tab (notice all the editable elements are highlighted)

2. Select whichever element you desire to edit from either table or list

3. Click the blue Edit button in the [cf:Element Tab.name]

4. Edit and save

If you are interested in learning how to put bulleted lists and tables into your views please refer to the greater MDK Manual for information on how to get started in Magic Draw.

elements.author: igomes
elements.name: How Do I Log In to View Editor?
elements.qualifiedName: /////Architectural Patterns & Examples/////How Do I Log In to View Editor?
elements.documentation:
If you are reading this manual in your web browser, then congratulations! You have successfully logged in to the View Editor.

 

For those operating on paper or other electronic copies please follow the following procedure so that you too can be one of those lucky people.

 

Please note that the only browser officially supported by the MDev team is Google Chrome. It can be downloaded free of charge for all OS platforms from the Chrome download page.

 

  1. Point your Chrome web browser to the desired View Editor server. Europa users tend to use "https://europaems.jpl.nasa.gov", while JPL community users tend to use "https://ems.jpl.nasa.gov". Individual projects may also have their own server.
  2. When prompted, login using your JPL ID and password. NOTE: Non-US Persons do not have access to Europa EMS. For more information please contact your task manager or Export Control Officer.
  3. You will then be sent to your homepage, or "dashboard". You can find sites using either the site tool in the top bar or within the site "dashlet". These sites are the same sites the model is linked to (see MDK manual). Some sites are public, but others require an invite.
  4. From the site, you can connect to the view editor. Often a shortcut to the site's DocWeb is listed in the important links dashlet. 
  5. Log in again using your JPL ID and password. (Note that you might be prompted to log in more than once.)
  6. Success! You should now be able to access and view documents within the View Editor!

elements.author: vritikas
elements.name: FilterByDiagramType
elements.documentation:
The FilerByDiagramType operation goes through a data set and looks at the elements which are diagrams. The user can decide which type of diagram is of interest to them, and display the names of only those diagrams in their document. 

We will illustrate this operation using the model where this document and it's elements reside. We know that within the package (called "Document Elements) are many viewpoint method diagrams that are used to display the examples. The pictures below show the containment tree (left) with the Document Elements package and the diagram (right) where the view for this section is linked to the FilterByDiagramType Viewpoint. Note, the actual viewpoint diagrams are a couple levels below the Viewpoints package within the Document Elements package. 

From the FilterByDiagramType Viewpoint block, we create the FilterByDiagramType Viewpoint Method Diagram (see previous sections for how to create a viewpoint method diagram). Once in the diagram, we drag an initial node into the diagram to start the activity. Next, we need to use a Collect function so we have something to filter. In this case, we choose "CollectOwnedElements" and select the depth to be 0 so we collect all owned elements at all levels (refer to section above for more about "CollectOwnedElements"). In the case of this example, the "FilterByDiagramType" operation exposes the "Document Elements," as shown above, thus "CollectOwnedElements" will collect everything owned by "Document Elements." The initial node is connected to "CollectOwnedElements" with a control flow. Next, we drag a "FilterByDiagramType" block onto the diagram, as shown in the picture below.

Going into the specification for "FilterByDiagramType," go to the "DiagramTypeChoosable" section and select the viewpoint method diagram via the drop-down menu. As you can see, there are many diagram types that a user could filter by to suit their needs. It is also possible to filter by more than one diagram type (by clicking the "+" button), if necessary. Once this is complete, make sure that include is checked under the "IncludeChoosable" section, which specifies that we would like to include only the viewpoint method diagrams in our output, instead of everything but the viewpoint method diagrams. Next we drag a "BulletedList" block onto the diagram to create a simple bulleted list with our results. Within the specification for "BulletedList," set "Ordered List" to be false, check "Stereotype Property Names," and check "Show Targets." Finally, drag an activity final node onto the diagram, and connect all the elements on the diagram with control flows, as shown in the picture above.

elements.author: vritikas
elements.name: Pattern Overview
elements.documentation:
Behavior is defined as a change of state of the system over time. State Variables describe properties of the system that can change with time. Mathematically they can be defined as functions of time, or functions that have time in the domain of the function. By declaring a state variable as a function of time we express the fact that that property can change over time -- i.e., that a behavior exists -- but have not yet constrained precisely what that behavior is. The actual behavior is defined by parametric relationships on that state variable property. For example, F=ma expresses a parametric relationship between two state variable properties F and a (assuming mass is constant).

In SysML behavior is primarily expressed through State Variable properties defined in Characterizations and parametric relations between those properties.

We can use the added semantics of SysML behaviors (state machines, activities, etc.) to help express some of these relationships, particularly how temporal relationships relate to each other and to time.

SysML and UML natively support modeling of certain kinds of behaviors in the form of state machines, activities, and sequences. They also implicitly support the modeling of behaviors through parametric diagrams that can define functions relating properties of the system.

This pattern elaborates those existing patterns to clarify a number of ambiguities in those patterns.

elements.author: vritikas
elements.name: What are the OCL Black Box Expressions?
elements.qualifiedName: /////Architectural Patterns & Examples/////What are the OCL Black Box Expressions?
elements.documentation:
Some functions were added to OCL as shorthand for some common operations.

  • m(), member(), or members() returns the owned elements
    • m('text') gets the member whose name or type is 'text'
    • m('likes').oclAsType(Dependency).target
  • r(), relationship(), or relationships() returns all relationships owned or for which the element is a target
    • r('likes') gets all of the relationships of name or type 'likes'
    • r('likes').oclAsType(Dependency).target
  • n(), name(), or names() returns the name
  • t(), type(), or types() returns the type.  t() and types() return all types (Stereotypes, metaclass, and Java classes and interfaces).
    • t('atypical') returns the type, atypical, for input with a type f that name
  • s(), stereotype(), or stereotypes() returns the Stereotypes.  This is basically short for appliedStereotypeInstance.classifier.  s() and stereotypes() should return all stereotypes, and stereotype() should just return one.
  • e(), evaluate(), or eval() evaluates an ocl expression retrieved from an element
  • value() returns the value of a property or slot
  • owners() returns owner and owner's owners, recursively
  • log() prints to Message Window in choice of color
  • run(View/Viewpoint) runs DocGen on a single View or Viewpoint with specified inputs and get the result

 The following Model is used to demonstrate the various capabilities of the black box expressions.

elements.author: vritikas
elements.name: How Do I Input Text Into Documents?
elements.qualifiedName: /////Architectural Patterns & Examples////How Do I Input Text Into Documents?
elements.documentation:
In general, it is easier to input text directly in the view editor (and then import it into the model) and to create tables with viewpoints (discussed in Section 3). However, you can also use the methods in this section.

For text in documentations, you can use plain text or html.

For plain text:

If all you have is a simple sentence or paragraph, this is enough. Newlines will be ignored.

If you know docbook or want specialized docbook tags to be included, this is also the way to go. Simply type in the docbook markup (make sure you have valid docbook tags!)

For html:

Check the html checkbox in magicdraw on any text or documentation field. DocGen will convert html tags to docbook. For the html conversion, there are some limitations to what html tags you can use. In the Magicdraw Advance HTML Editor, you can look at the HTML source tab to see if your html source can be successfully converted into DocBook. Below are a list of tags converted:

  • p
  • ul
  • ol
  • li
  • b
  • i
  • u
  • a
  • sub
  • sup
  • pre

Examples:

A paragraph

  • unordered list item
    • nested list item
  1. ordered list item

Bold Italic underline or hyperlinked text, email, and subscripts and superscripts .

  

Other preformmatted text like code and xml (the < chars in xml still have to be escaped in the html source). 
<xml>
      <sometag>
      helllloo and other stuff <>
      </sometag>
</xml>

All other styles or font setting will be stripped off as docgen processes it.

Tables made in the Advanced HTML Editor may also be supported, but there must be a <caption></caption> as the first child of the table. The caption will be used as the title of the table generated. You'll have to add this in the HTML source tab.

HTML Table
 example  html
 table  in html editor

 

If you don't want a title for your table, make it an informal table. In the HTML source tab, put in <table class="informal" at the table tag. Don't put in the caption. This also means this table won't get an entry in the table of contents.

 html  table
 without  caption (title)

 

  You can access html on the magicdraw side by going to the specification window and documentation and selecting html.  You can also directly insert html on view editor.

elements.author: vritikas
elements.name: What Is OCL and How Do I Use It?
elements.qualifiedName: /////Architectural Patterns & Examples/////What Is OCL and How Do I Use It?
elements.documentation:
OCL Primer By Bradly Clement

The Object Constraint Language (OCL) is a text language (a subset of QVT) that can be used to customize views and viewpoints in various ways that otherwise may require writing external code in Jython, QVT, Java, etc.  You can use OCL to specify how to collect, filter, sort, constrain, and present model data.

OCL syntax can be tricky since it accesses model information through the UML metamodel (see the UML metamodel manual in your Magicdraw installation directory, under manual).  Here we try to give some tips on how to write OCL expressions to more easily customize views without having to write external scripts in Jython, Java, QVT, etc.


OCL Resources

For help with OCL, you can try the OCL Cheat Sheet or OCL Helper or search the web for example OCL.  Some example will also be given in the next two sections below.

NoMagic's UML metamodel specifies what objects can be referenced in an OCL expression for the different UML types.  A pdf manual of the metamodel can be found in your MagicDraw installation in the manual folder.  If you use Eclipse, try opening the Metamodel Explorer view from the menu: Window -> Show View -> Other.  There may be many metamodels, but look for the com.nomagic.uml2 metamodel.  There is a button on the view where you can search for a type, but be careful since there may be more than one UML metamodel.  You want MagicDraw's UML metamodel.   There is also a button for showing inherited members that can be referenced in OCL.



Viewpoint Elements

<<CollectByExpression>> Collect elements using an OCL expression.  This works like other collect stereotypes.

<<FilterByExpression>> Filter a collection using an OCL expression.    This works like other filter stereotypes.

<<SortByExpression>> Sort a collection using an OCL expression.    This works like other sort stereotypes.

<<Constraint>> You can add this stereotype to a comment or an action in an activity diagram to evaluate an OCL expression on the action's results.  The expression should return true or false.  If false, the constraint is violated, and the violation will be added to the validation results panel.  A constraint comment can be anchored to multiple actions to apply to all of the actions' results separately.

<<TableExpressionColumn>> Apply an OCL expression to the target elements.  This can be used to chain operations on elements and relatonships that would be otherwise be difficult or impossible.

<<CustomTable>> A CustomTable allows columns to all be specified as OCL expressions in one viewpoint element.  Target elements each have a row in the table.  Title, headings, and captions are specified as with other tables.
